  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most Brisbane sellers focus their preparation effort on the start of the auction campaign: the photography, the first open home, the price guide. By the time auction day arrives, they are running on nerves and assuming the hard work is done. It is not. The week before auction, and the morning of auction day itself, contain several decisions that genuinely affect the price you achieve. Sellers who treat this week as a structured checklist rather than an anxious wait consistently produce better outcomes.</p>

      <p>This is a companion article to our walkthrough of what happens on auction day. The focus here is on what you should be doing in the lead-up, so that when the hammer is about to fall you are not making important decisions on adrenaline alone.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Seven to ten days out: the buyer pool conversation</h2>
      <p>By the final full week of campaign, your agent should have a clear picture of the buyer pool. They should be able to name the genuine contenders, tell you who has registered (or is about to), who is pre-approved, and what price feedback each has given. This is the moment to sit down with your agent for an honest one-hour conversation about where the auction is realistically heading.</p>

      <p>Ask specifically: how many groups will register to bid, what is the top of the buyer range based on confirmed interest, and what has happened with comparable properties in the last fortnight. If your agent cannot answer these with specifics, the campaign has not generated enough depth and you need to know that now, not on Saturday morning.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Five days out: confirm the contract and the legal paperwork</h2>
      <p>Your solicitor or conveyancer should have your contract of sale finalised and reviewed well before auction week. On the Monday of auction week, double-check that the contract documents are ready to exchange on the day, that any special conditions you want included are correctly drafted, and that the deposit amount and settlement terms match what your agent has been quoting to buyers.</p>

      <p>Unconditional auction contracts in Queensland have no cooling-off period. This means the paperwork must be exactly right at the moment contracts are signed. Small errors (an incorrect lot number, a missing disclosure document, a contradictory special condition) can create genuine problems at the point of signing or in the days after. This is the week to catch them.</p>

      <p>If you are selling a unit or townhouse, the body corporate records search, strata report, and disclosure statement must be up to date and available to serious buyers. Buyers often make their final decision to register based on the content of those documents. Making them available late, or in incomplete form, reduces the number of registered bidders you end up with.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Four days out: final presentation review</h2>
      <p>Walk through the property with your agent on Tuesday or Wednesday and note anything that has drifted since the campaign began. Four weeks of open homes, rain, and general wear tends to dull presentation. The lawn needs a fresh cut. The front pavers might need a pressure wash. Styling props may have shifted. If you are still living in the home, clutter has almost certainly crept back into the bathroom and kitchen benches.</p>

      <p>This is also the point to review the front of the property from the street. Street appeal on auction day matters, because buyers arriving for the auction will form (or re-form) an impression in the thirty seconds between parking and walking through the gate. A tired front garden or a full bin at the kerb is not where you want the buyer pool starting from.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Two days out: the reserve conversation</h2>
      <p>Your agent will sit down with you the day before or two days before auction to agree on your reserve price. The reserve is the minimum price at which you will sell. It is strictly confidential between you and your agent.</p>

      <p>Prepare for this meeting. Review the campaign feedback, look at the final comparable sales, and think honestly about the price you will not accept. The reserve should be set by data, not by the number you wish the property was worth. If your agent's recommended reserve is materially below your expectation, ask them to walk you through the specific buyer feedback that supports their number. A well-run auction campaign produces enough information for the reserve to be defensible in writing.</p>

      <p>Do not set a reserve so high that the property cannot reach it. A property that passes in because the reserve was unrealistic sends a negative signal to the buyer pool and complicates the post-auction negotiation. A property that sells on reserve or above is, almost by definition, sold for more than any individual buyer was willing to pay before the auction started. That is the whole point of running the campaign this way.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The day before: logistics</h2>
      <p>Confirm the auctioneer, the agent team, and the on-site plan. Where will the auction be held (front garden, living room, undercover area)? Where will buyers park? Where will contracts be signed? Who is responsible for moving registered bidders to the signing table if the property sells? Your agent should have answers for all of this.</p>

      <p>Confirm what time the final inspection opens in the morning. Most Brisbane auctions have a thirty-minute open home immediately before the scheduled auction start. The property should be at photography-standard presentation for that final inspection.</p>

      <p>Make a plan for yourself. Will you stay on site and watch from a discreet distance, or go for a walk and return for the result? Both are reasonable. What is not reasonable is being visibly present in the auction crowd, which can inhibit genuine buyers from bidding freely.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Auction morning: three key decisions</h2>
      <p>Three decisions happen quickly on auction morning and they all need to be made calmly.</p>

      <p>First, your reserve. Your agent will confirm (or renegotiate) the reserve with you after the final open home, when they have a last read of the registered bidders and the mood in the room. If the open home attendance is much stronger than expected, you may want to hold the reserve firm. If it is softer and registrations are fewer than hoped, your agent may recommend a small adjustment. Trust your agent's read of the room, but make the final call yourself.</p>

      <p>Second, vendor bids. In Queensland, the auctioneer can bid on your behalf up to the reserve, provided each such bid is announced as a vendor bid. Vendor bids can be useful to get the auction started or to lift it from a low opening. They should not be used to push the price above reserve or to mask the fact that there is only one genuine bidder. Agree with your auctioneer in advance on how vendor bids will be used and at what increments.</p>

      <p>Third, what to do if bidding stalls below reserve. If bidding plateaus short of reserve, your agent may pause the auction and consult you privately about lowering the reserve. This is a real-time decision, and a hard one. Think about it in advance. A useful frame is: would you accept this price if it came in as a private treaty offer the next day? If yes, it is probably the right price to sell at. If no, you should hold, knowing the property may pass in and be negotiated afterwards.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">If the property passes in</h2>
      <p>Not every auction ends under the hammer, and passing in is not a failure. What matters is how the post-auction conversation is handled. The highest bidder has the first right to negotiate with you privately, and this negotiation should happen immediately, while the buyer is still emotionally engaged and your agent is in a position to close the deal.</p>

      <p>Have a fallback position in mind before the auction starts. If the property passes in at (for example) $1.45 million and your reserve was $1.5 million, what is the lowest number you will accept from that highest bidder in the private negotiation that follows? Decide that in advance, not in the car after.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">After the hammer</h2>
      <p>If the property sells under the hammer, contracts are exchanged immediately. You should have your phone charged, your identification close to hand, and a clear head for the paperwork that follows. Take a breath. Congratulate the buyer. Move through the signing calmly. The settlement clock starts from the moment contracts are signed.</p>

      <p>In the twenty-four hours after auction day, do three things: confirm in writing with your solicitor that the contract has been lodged; make sure a copy of the signed contract is in your records; and give yourself permission to be tired. A well-prepared auction campaign is genuinely demanding, and once it is over, so is the most stressful part of the sale process.</p>

